<subSubSection pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="preliminary conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Preliminary conservation status</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
(
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Annales de Biologie" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B56" refString="IUCN, 2014. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 11., http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 11" url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2014">IUCN 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Least Concern (LC). EOO 165,095 km2 (LC), AOO 40 km2 (EN). In common with other members of the ANS clade in Madagascar, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a relatively wide distribution, resulting in an EOO indicating lack of immediate conservation concern. The paucity of collections, indicative of local rarity, coupled with the ongoing habitat threats in Madagascar, however, do indicate monitoring and further collection to assess local and regional rarity is necessary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a fairly common liana or shrub with shallowly cordate or truncate leaves clustered towards tips of branches, large (to 3 cm in diameter) violet or purple flowers, and large anthers 4-5 mm long. The pubescence of den 
<pageBreakToken pageId="41" pageNumber="42" start="start">dritic</pageBreakToken>
trichomes up to 0.3-0.5 mm long is visible with the naked eye on the petioles, pedicels, inflorescences and abaxial sides of the leaves (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Flowers of species in the ANS clade. A Solanum africanum Mill. (South Africa, Rebelo s. n. - no herbarium voucher) B Solanum imamense Dunal (Madagascar, Rakotavao 5128) C Solanum madagascariense Dunal (Madagascar, Vorontsova et al. 498) D Solanum sambiranense D'Arcy &amp; Rakot. (Madagascar, Randrianasolo 580) E Solanum terminale Forssk. (Kenya, Vorontsova et al. 93) F Solanum truncicola Bitter (Madagascar, Antilahimena et al. 7846). Photo credits: A Tony Rebelo; B Charles Rakotavao; C, E Maria Vorontsova; D Richard Randrianasolo; E Patrice Antilahimena." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.66.8457.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/95573" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">1B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Habit and fruits of species of the ANS clade. A Habit of Solanum sambiranense D'Arcy &amp; Rakot. (Madagascar, Randrianasolo 580) B Fruit of Solanum imamense Dunal (Madagascar, Rakotavao 5128) C Fruit of Solanum terminale Forssk., pointed form (Angola, Goyder et al. 7749) D Fruit of Solanum terminale Forssk., globose form (Tanzania, Tepe et al. 2783). Photo credits: A Richard Randrianasolo; B Charles Rakotavao; C David Goyder; D Maria Vorontsova." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.66.8457.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/95575" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">2B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar and possibly closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum betroka" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betroka">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum betroka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from southern Madagascar and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum sambiranense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sambiranense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum sambiranense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from northern Madagascar, and perhaps also the rare and poorly known 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum ivohibe" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ivohibe">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum ivohibe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the province of Fianarantsoa. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum betroka" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betroka">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum betroka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its inflorescences with 7-13 (versus 1-3) flowers, larger floral parts, and leaves that are always entire (versus leaves that are frequently lobed). 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum sambiranense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sambiranense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum sambiranense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its ovate leaves 2.5-5 cm long (versus elliptic to obovate leaves 5-10 cm long) and looser dendritic trichomes 0.2-0.5 mm (versus less than 0.1 mm) long. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum ivohibe" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ivohibe">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum ivohibe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its ovate leaves less than 5 cm long (versus elliptic to obovate leaves 5-7 cm long), cordate to short attenuate (versus long attenuate) leaf base, and calyx lobes more than 2 mm (versus less than 2 mm) long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a broad ecological profile occurring occasionally in dry to mesic parts of the island in the western, central, and southern ecoregions (
<bibRefCitation author="Humbert, H" journalOrPublisher="Annales de Biologie" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" pagination="195 - 204" refId="B55" refString="Humbert, H, 1955. Les territoires phytogeographiques de Madagascar. Leur cartographie. Colloque sur les regions ecologiques du globe, Paris 1954. Annales de Biologie 31: 195 - 204" title="Les territoires phytogeographiques de Madagascar. Leur cartographie. Colloque sur les regions ecologiques du globe, Paris 1954." volume="31" year="1955">Humbert 1955</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Faramalala, MH" journalOrPublisher="Universite Paul Sabatier, Toulouse" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" refId="B46" refString="Faramalala, MH, 1988. Etude de la vegetation de Madagascar a l'aide des donnees spaciales. Universite Paul Sabatier, Toulouse" title="Etude de la vegetation de Madagascar a l'aide des donnees spaciales" year="1988">Faramalala 1988</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Faramalala, MH" journalOrPublisher="Universite Paul Sabatier, Toulouse" pageId="108" pageNumber="109" refId="B47" refString="Faramalala, MH, 1995. Formations vegetales et domaine forestier national de Madagascar. In: Conservation International (et al.)." title="Formations vegetales et domaine forestier national de Madagascar." volumeTitle="Conservation International (et al.)." year="1995">1995</bibRefCitation>
). In the southern part of its distribution range it is sympatric with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum betroka" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="betroka">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum betroka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and in the northern part of the range with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum sambiranense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sambiranense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum sambiranense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dunal" authorityYear="1852" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense subsp. var. var. grandiflorum" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="imamense" subSpecies="var." variety="grandiflorum">Solanum imamense var. grandiflorum</taxonomicName>
was accepted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bitter, G" journalOrPublisher="Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="416 - 506" refId="B5" refString="Bitter, G, 1917. Solana Africana II. Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie 54: 416 - 506" title="Solana Africana II." volume="54" year="1917">Bitter (1917)</bibRefCitation>
but synonymised with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="D'Arcy, WG" journalOrPublisher="Museum National D'Histoire Naturelle, Paris" pageId="107" pageNumber="108" pagination="1 - 146" refId="B25" refString="D'Arcy, WG, Rakotozafy, A, 1994. Flore de Madagascar et des Comores. Museum National D'Histoire Naturelle, Paris: 1 - 146" title="Flore de Madagascar et des Comores" year="1994">
<normalizedToken originalValue="D’Arcy">D'Arcy</normalizedToken>
and Rakotozafy (1994)
</bibRefCitation>
. It differs from the type variety by flower size and pubescence density, but the variation in both characters is continuous. The type specimens of both were collected by W. Bojer in central Madagascar. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. G. D' Arcy &amp; A. Rakotozafy" authorityYear="1994" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum ankazobe" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ankazobe">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum ankazobe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described on the basis of three collections, and was distinguished by its small leaves, smaller calyx tube, irregular tearing of the calyx and wider ovary. The type collection of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. G. D' Arcy &amp; A. Rakotozafy" authorityYear="1994" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum ankazobe" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ankazobe">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum ankazobe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Perrier de la 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bâthie">Bathie</normalizedToken>
9615
</emphasis>
) has leaves that fall within the range of variation in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while other specimens cited have smaller floral parts (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Perrier de la 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bâthie">Bathie</normalizedToken>
9577
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">9579</emphasis>
). We consider these specimens to fall within the range of variation represented in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum imamense" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="imamense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum imamense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and treat 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. G. D' Arcy &amp; A. Rakotozafy" authorityYear="1994" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum ankazobe" order="Solanales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ankazobe">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Solanum ankazobe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym.
</paragraph>
